# Amazon Linux / RHEL / CentOS
ğŸ“Œ Important Notes
1. Set passwords for all users (root, ec2-user, sonarqube)
   Command: sudo passwd <username>

2. SonarQube runs on port: 9000

3. Default Login:
      Username: admin
      Password: admin

ğŸ§° Prerequisites

# EC2 instance with minimum t3.medium (2 CPU, 4 GB RAM)

# Amazon Linux 2 / RHEL / CentOS

# Root or sudo access

# Internet connectivity

ğŸŸ¢ Step 1: Update the System Packages

# Purpose:
# Ensures all system packages are up-to-date and avoids dependency issues.

   sudo yum update -y

ğŸŸ¢ Step 2: Install Java 17 (Required for SonarQube)

# Purpose:
# SonarQube requires Java 17 to run properly.

   sudo yum install java-17-amazon-corretto-devel -y

âœ… Verify Java Installation

   java -version

ğŸŸ¢ Step 3: Create a Dedicated SonarQube User

# Purpose:
# SonarQube should not run as root for security reasons.

   sudo useradd sonarqube
   sudo passwd sonarqube

ğŸŸ¢ Step 4: Add SonarQube User to Sudoers

# Purpose:
# Allows sonarqube user to execute administrative commands when required.

# Option 1: Add to Wheel Group (Recommended)

   sudo usermod -aG wheel sonarqube

# Option 2: Using visudo (Advanced)

 sudo visudo


# Add:

sonarqube ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: ALL

ğŸŸ¢ Step 5: Download SonarQube Community Edition

# Purpose:
# Downloads the official SonarQube binary package.

   wget https://binaries.sonarsource.com/Distribution/sonarqube/sonarqube-10.1.0.73491.zip

ğŸŸ¢ Step 6: Move SonarQube to /opt Directory

# Purpose:
# /opt is the standard location for third-party applications.

   sudo mv sonarqube-10.1.0.73491.zip /opt/

   cd /opt

ğŸŸ¢ Step 7: Install Unzip & Extract SonarQube

# Purpose:
# Extracts SonarQube binaries for execution.

   sudo yum install unzip -y
   sudo unzip sonarqube-10.1.0.73491.zip

ğŸŸ¢ Step 8: Set Ownership to SonarQube User

# Purpose:
# Ensures SonarQube has permission to access its own files.

   sudo chown -R sonarqube:sonarqube sonarqube-10.1.0.73491

ğŸŸ¢ Step 9: Switch to SonarQube User

# Purpose:
# Runs SonarQube using the dedicated non-root user.

   su - sonarqube

ğŸŸ¢ Step 10: Configure System Limits (Very Important)

# Purpose:
# SonarQube requires higher file descriptors and virtual memory.

# Edit sysctl config
   sudo vi /etc/sysctl.conf


# Add:

   vm.max_map_count=262144
   fs.file-max=65536


# Apply changes:

   sudo sysctl -p

ğŸŸ¢ Step 11: Configure User Limits

# Purpose:
# Prevents SonarQube startup failures related to open files.

   sudo vi /etc/security/limits.conf


# Add:

   sonarqube   -   nofile   65536
   sonarqube   -   nproc    4096

ğŸŸ¢ Step 12: Start SonarQube Server

# Purpose:
# Starts the SonarQube application.

   cd /opt/sonarqube-10.1.0.73491/bin/linux-x86-64/
   ./sonar.sh start

ğŸŸ¢ Step 13: Check SonarQube Status

# Purpose:
# Verifies whether SonarQube started successfully.

   ./sonar.sh status


# Expected output:

# SonarQube is running

ğŸŸ¢ Step 14: Open Port 9000 in Security Group

# Purpose:
# Allows external access to SonarQube UI.

# Go to EC2 â†’ Security Group

# Add Inbound Rule:

# Type: Custom TCP

# Port: 9000

# Source: Your IP / 0.0.0.0/0 (for testing)

ğŸŸ¢ Step 15: Access SonarQube UI

# Purpose:
# Access the SonarQube dashboard from browser.

   http://<EC2-Public-IP>:9000

ğŸ” Default Credentials
   Username: admin
   Password: admin


